Description.val:
The TRIDENT II (D5) missiles will be carried on OHIO Class Fleet Ballistic Missile Submarines through 2042 and will be the initial payload for the COLUMBIA Class Fleet Ballistic Missile Submarines.  The D5 Life Extension (D5LE) program will ensure that the United States continues to maintain a highly survivable strategic deterrent well into the 21st century.  The TRIDENT II missile (1) enhances fleet ballistic missile submarine survivability as it increases the sea launched ballistic missile range at full payload to exploit the total patrol area available to the TRIDENT submarine, (2) minimizes total weapon system costs as it has increased the sea launched ballistic missile payload to the level permitted by the size of the TRIDENT submarine launch tube, thereby allowing mission capability to be achieved with fewer submarines, and (3) has added an efficient hard target kill capability to the sea launched ballistic missiles.

D5 Life Extension Costs Include:

Joint Fuze Sustainment: Includes the procurement and assembly of the Arming Fuzing & Firing (AF&F) kits in support of the National Defense Strategy.

Production Support: Funding supports D5 Life Extension (D5LE) system integration, D5LE tooling and test equipment, D5LE Flight Test Instrumentation and Analysis, support for the new Test Missile Kits (TMK's), and D5LE end of production costs.

Guidance Hardware: Includes procurement of subcomponents necessary for a complete Guidance System which consists of an Inertial Measurement Unit (IMU) and Electronics Assembly (EA).  Within the IMU and EA there are numerous sub-components which are included in this cost element including Guidance Circuit Card Assemblies (CCA), Guidance Accelerometer Sensors (PIGA), Interferometric Fiber Optic Gyros (IFOG), and associated production support.

Fleet Return Missile Electronic Strategic Systems Programs Alterations (SPALT) Kits: Includes procurement of the four Missile Electronics Packages and associated production support in order to extend the life of the D5 Missile to align with the OHIO Class life.





Operating and Support Costs Include:

Warhead Components: Includes production of the W76-1/Mk4A Reentry Body assembly and associated support equipment including Reentry Body (RB) cabling and Reentry Body Shells and supports the efforts required to produce a low yield variant (76-2).

The Shape Stable Nose Tip (SSNT) Program: The Mk4B SSNT (formerly referenced as Mk4A SSNT) effort will convert RB forward shell assemblies (FSA's) from legacy carbon composite nose tips to SSNT's in order to provide more consistent and predictable flight performance characteristics of the weapon system.

Tooling, Test/Support Equipment: Includes the refresh and/or replacement of aging Test/Evaluation equipment experiencing obsolescence.

Containers: Includes procurement of shipping containers for post DD250 D5 Missile components, test instrumentation, and Mk4/Mk5 Reentry Bodies.

Systems integration/planning: Provides for system component management and integration as well as master schedule oversight and planning.

Supportability Modifications/SPALT Insertion: Provides for installation costs for missile Strategic Program Alterations (SPALT's), SPALTS are converting D5 missiles to D5LE missiles.  These costs also fund missile processing efforts that include the hands-on and hands-off support needed to DD250 missiles.  Support includes radiographic inspection, non-missile production related tasks for mechanics, technicians, production planners and controllers, and missile system engineers.  

End of Production Missile and Guidance Costs: Provides for end of production spares as well as costs associated with shutting down production lines.

Solid Rocket Motor's (SRM's) and Post Boost Control Systems (PBCS's): Includes procurement of SRM's, PBCS's, and all associated costs including production requalification, HMX procurement, tooling, railcar support and Production Evaluation Testing and Static Firing.

Production Support/Missile Hardware: First Stage Thrust Vector Control Gas Generators (which include Servoactuators and Gas Hydraulic Assemblies).

Justification.val:
Funding in the TRIDENT II Mods line is required to continue the procurement of TRIDENT II missiles and currently supports the life-extension of the D5 missile. 

TRIDENT II MODS - D5 Life Extension Program P-5:

The FY 2021 request of $602.907 million for the D5 Life Extension (D5LE) Program supports the production of the redesigned guidance system and missile electronics packages, which must be replaced to support the extended service life of the Ohio Class Submarines.  FY 2021 funding procures missile electronic and guidance SPALT kits as well as other critical components required to support the extended SSBN hull life for a 14 SSBN TRIDENT II program.  FY21 Joint Fuze Arming Fuzing & Firing (AF&F) kits quantities increase to meet capacity capability of the production lines.  The variation in quantities per year is due to shared utilization of the National Nuclear Security Administration and Department of Energy production capacity. The unit costs fluctuation is a result of life of part buys and commercial off the shelf items required to support assembly in addition to AF&F quantity changes.     

The lowered request from FY 2020 to FY 2021 in Production Support (-$52.095M) reflects decreased production support requirements in Test Missile Kit (TMK) and Thermal Impact Protection System (TIPS) hardware, reduction of TMK Long Lead materials, and D5 LE Flight test Instrumentation purchases. 

Fleet Return Missile Electronic SPALT Kits growth ($4.524M) is due to increased purchase quantities of Flight Control Electronic Assemblies and Interlocks.  Quantities procured support the conversion of D5 missiles to D5LE missiles and are determined by fleet availability and when the D5 missiles are available for the conversion process.

TRIDENT II MODS - Operating and Support Costs P-5:

The FY 2021 request of $570.930 million for Operating and Support Costs funds efforts associated with the sustainment of TRIDENT II (D5) missiles to include system integration efforts, replacement of aging rocket motors, refreshes and replacement of D5 legacy tooling and test support equipment, Supportability Mods/Strategic Programs Alteration (SPALT) Insertion, Warhead Components and Shape Stable Nose Tip (SSNT).



Shape Stable Nose Tip (SSNT) efforts increase ($18.005M) in FY21 as reentry body conversions continue.  Specifically, FY21 procures additional nose tip billet materials to support material qualification testing and forward shell conversion from legacy carbon composite nose tips to Shape Stable Nose Tip, and modifying and updating Reentry Body documentation.  The nosetip billet materials is transitioning from development (LI 0101221N RDTE PRJ 2021) to production.
 
Tooling, Test/Support Equipment efforts increase ($12.935M) as required to maintain and procure special interface gages and Special Support Equipment electrical and mechanical spare/repair parts.  The FY21 increase is attributable to procuring Kneel Down Transporters, inter-facility transportation equipment, used to support missile processing and disposal efforts.  Additionally, FY21 increased funding procures High Voltage Detonator Bridgewire and Test System Test Consoles, as well as Command Sequencer, JBOX, and Power Distribution Unit Test Consoles. 

Cost Element 2.3 HMX funding increases ($2.945M) in FY21 in support of increased HMX procurements.  The FY21 fluctuations in HMX procurement are due to differences in US/UK procurement ratios, variation in the Performance Evaluation Testing (PET) Schedule and the type of motor being tested (first stage, second stage, or third stage) and the requirement to maintain a minimum supply of HMX to mitigate risks.   

Within Production Support/Missile Hardware, FY21 funding increases ($24.125M) as production begins for First Stage Thrust Vector Control Gas Generators (which include Servoactuators and Gas Hydraulic Assemblies).  FS TVC GGs are energetics which are used to control First Stage motors flight.  Many of the missile hardware energetic components were not intended to be in service this long and due to their limited life these energetic components need to be requalified, reproduced, and procured due to safety concerns associated with a manned platform.    
 
Warhead Components funding reduced in FY21 ($-12.08M) due to Alternate Release Assembly Fleet assemblies and the procurement of Thermal Protection System (TPS) being completed in FY20.
